**who —** DICTYOSTELIUM — a life-science sphere — the brainless mind

**what —** When food runs out, tens of thousands of lone amoebae — each a separate single-celled creature — stream together by chemical pulse into one body: a crawling slug, then a stalk that sacrifices a fifth of its cells so the rest can rise as spores. A many-celled animal that is really a society, voting with chemistry to become one.

**where —** intelligence without a brain  Framework inputs: the living; the rule; the signal; the open question  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** When food runs out, tens of thousands of lone amoebae — each a separate single-celled creature — stream together by chemical pulse into one body: a crawling slug, then a stalk that sacrifices a fifth of its cells so the rest can rise as spores. A many-celled animal that is really a society, voting with chemistry to become one.

**how —** Crystallized from the public record of the science.

